# gemini-firefox

This project is a stripped-down, standalone tool and is **inspired by and
derived from** the [Oracle](https://github.com/steipete/oracle) CLI by
Peter Steinberger ([@steipete](https://github.com/steipete)), which is
licensed under the MIT License.

## Origin & inspiration

The Gemini web (cookie) client and the Firefox cookie-extraction approach
originated in Oracle's `src/gemini-web/` directory
([steipete/oracle](https://github.com/steipete/oracle)). This project ports
the essential, working pieces of that Gemini-web client to a minimal,
zero-dependency Node script that reads session cookies from Firefox instead
of Chrome.

Key upstream sources this project builds on:

- **Oracle** (`steipete/oracle`) — the original Gemini web cookie client
  (`src/gemini-web/client.ts`, `executor.ts`, `models.ts`) and the layered
  cookie-loader design. MIT licensed, Copyright (c) 2026 Peter Steinberger.
- The modern Gemini `StreamGenerate` request envelope, the model-selector
  header format, and the length-prefixed response framing were reverse-
  engineered against `gemini.google.com`; the current request/response
  shapes were validated against the live web UI and cross-referenced with
  the [HanaokaYuzu/Gemini-API](https://github.com/HanaokaYuzu/Gemini-API)
  reference (also MIT).

## What this project changed / added

- Removed all Chrome/keychain/CDP dependencies — reads Firefox's plaintext
  `cookies.sqlite` via the built-in `node:sqlite` instead.
- Added Firefox Multi-Account Container targeting (`--container`).
- Modernized the internal `gemini.google.com` request protocol (the upstream
  HTTP client was returning error `1061`; this project refreshes the
  69/92-element `f.req` payload, the 12/17-element model-selector header,
  the `cfb2h`/`FdrFJe` session tokens, and `rt=c` streaming).
- Added the modern two-step resumable upload flow
  (`push.clients6.google.com/upload/`) for file attachments.
- Standalone CLI with zero external dependencies (Node built-ins only).

Grateful credit to Peter Steinberger for the original work.
